## 12. GRPC (RUST ↔ NODE.JS)

```typescript
// Node.js gRPC client — Pricing Engine
import { PricingServiceClient } from '../generated/pricing_grpc_pb';
import { credentials } from '@grpc/grpc-js';

@Injectable()
export class PricingClient {
  private client: PricingServiceClient;

  constructor(config: ConfigService) {
    this.client = new PricingServiceClient(
      config.get('PRICING_ENGINE_ADDR'), // e.g. pricing-engine:50051
      credentials.createInsecure(), // mTLS in production
    );
  }

  async getCurrentPrices(): Promise<ProductPrice[]> {
    return promisify(this.client.getCurrentPrices.bind(this.client))({});
  }
}
```

### Rules
- Proto files live in a shared `proto/` directory at repo root — single source of truth
- Generate TypeScript types from proto at build time — never handwrite them
- gRPC calls have explicit timeouts — never leave them unbounded
- Circuit breaker on gRPC calls from Node.js to Rust services — if Pricing Engine is down, serve cached Redis price
- Use mTLS between services in production — insecure credentials only in local dev

---

## 13. REDIS USAGE

```typescript
// Key naming convention — always namespaced
const KEYS = {
  idempotency: (provider: string, ref: string) => `idem:${provider}:${ref}`,
  virtualAccount: (orderId: string) => `vaccount:${orderId}`,
  session: (whatsappNumber: string) => `session:${whatsappNumber}`,
  price: (sku: string) => `price:${sku}`,
  velocity: (address: string, date: string) => `velocity:${address}:${date}`,
  confirmedTx: (chain: string, txHash: string) => `confirmed_tx:${chain}:${txHash}`,
} as const;
```

### Rules
- Every Redis key has an explicit TTL — no permanent keys for ephemeral data
- Key naming: `{namespace}:{identifier}` — never bare keys
- Never store sensitive data (private keys, gift codes unencrypted) in Redis
- Redis is cache and coordination layer — PostgreSQL is the system of record
- If Redis is unavailable, payment flows degrade gracefully (not fail hard) — except idempotency gates

---

## 14. API DESIGN

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT — consistent response envelope
interface ApiResponse<T> {
  success: boolean;
  data?: T;
  error?: { code: string; message: string };
  meta?: { timestamp: string; requestId: string };
}

// ✅ CORRECT — amounts always as strings
interface OrderResponse {
  id: string;
  status: string;
  amountNgn: string;     // "16000.00" — not 16000
  amountUsdc: string;    // "10.000000" — not 10
  createdAt: string;     // ISO 8601
}
```

### Rules
- All timestamps: ISO 8601 UTC strings — `2025-05-01T14:00:00.000Z`
- All amounts: decimal strings — never JSON numbers for money
- All IDs: UUIDs — never auto-increment integers exposed externally
- Versioned routes: `/api/v1/` — always, from day one
- Rate limiting per WhatsApp number on API Gateway — not just per IP
- 4xx errors always include a machine-readable `code` field for client handling

